00:43:18.986 --> 00:43:22.626 A:middle
So, one of the last things the
iCloud Dashboard helps you do is

00:43:22.626 --> 00:43:25.066 A:middle
move from development
into production.

00:43:25.376 --> 00:43:27.186 A:middle
So, as I talked about earlier,

00:43:27.286 --> 00:43:29.986 A:middle
we wanted the development
environment to be as quick

00:43:29.986 --> 00:43:31.556 A:middle
and easy to use as possible.

00:43:32.056 --> 00:43:34.076 A:middle
We wanted you to hit the
ground running, we wanted you

00:43:34.076 --> 00:43:37.046 A:middle
to just open up Xcode,
start typing some code,

00:43:37.046 --> 00:43:39.806 A:middle
save your record to the server,
and see immediate results.

00:43:40.496 --> 00:43:43.786 A:middle
And that all works great because
the server does just-in-time

00:43:43.786 --> 00:43:47.256 A:middle
schemas, but that's not very
efficient if we're working

00:43:47.256 --> 00:43:49.986 A:middle
in a public database that
might have millions of users.

00:43:50.066 --> 00:43:52.916 A:middle
We need to prepare some
things before we go

00:43:52.916 --> 00:43:55.946 A:middle
into the environment that all of
our customers are going to hit.

00:43:56.656 --> 00:43:59.216 A:middle
So, the way this works
is we've got our records,

00:43:59.326 --> 00:44:00.696 A:middle
we're developing
our app right now,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:59.326 --> 00:44:00.696 A:middle
we're developing
our app right now,

00:44:01.586 --> 00:44:03.916 A:middle
and we just created a record
for the very first time,

00:44:03.916 --> 00:44:05.896 A:middle
and we uploaded it in the
development environment.

00:44:07.076 --> 00:44:08.206 A:middle
The server is going to see that

00:44:08.256 --> 00:44:10.656 A:middle
and since this is the first
time it's seen a party,

00:44:10.656 --> 00:44:13.316 A:middle
it's going to automatically
create a new party record type.

00:44:13.316 --> 00:44:16.556 A:middle
And then for each of
these keys and values,

00:44:17.056 --> 00:44:19.986 A:middle
it's going to create an entry
in a schema, and it's going

00:44:19.986 --> 00:44:22.206 A:middle
to create an index on
every one of those values.

00:44:23.316 --> 00:44:26.606 A:middle
This index is what lets you
query for any value in a record.

00:44:27.096 --> 00:44:29.656 A:middle
So, while you're in development,
you can just run a query

00:44:29.656 --> 00:44:32.506 A:middle
and search on any value
for any key in a record.

00:44:33.966 --> 00:44:36.196 A:middle
And let's say we're going ahead
and we're developing this app

00:44:36.196 --> 00:44:38.686 A:middle
and we decide we want to
add an additional property,

00:44:38.686 --> 00:44:42.116 A:middle
so we decide we want to
have a background property

00:44:42.116 --> 00:44:43.356 A:middle
for the color of the party.

00:44:43.916 --> 00:44:45.556 A:middle
So, this party's
background is blue.

00:44:46.046 --> 00:44:47.556 A:middle
All we have to do is
upload that record.

00:44:48.116 --> 00:44:50.566 A:middle
It's going to send all those
other properties to the index,

00:44:51.156 --> 00:44:52.936 A:middle
and the server is
going to notice, "Oh,

00:44:52.936 --> 00:44:54.056 A:middle
there's a new property in here."

00:44:54.546 --> 00:44:57.146 A:middle
It's going to create a new
schema entry, build a new index,

00:44:57.536 --> 00:44:58.606 A:middle
and index that property.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:00.536 --> 00:45:03.006 A:middle
When you're ready to release
your app, you're going to want

00:45:03.006 --> 00:45:05.406 A:middle
to make sure you've run
everything in development first

00:45:05.506 --> 00:45:07.466 A:middle
so that you've built up
this just-in-time schema.

00:45:08.726 --> 00:45:11.476 A:middle
You're then going to use
the iCloud Dashboard to move

00:45:11.476 --> 00:45:13.896 A:middle
that schema from
development into production,

00:45:13.896 --> 00:45:15.826 A:middle
and you're going to want to
check all of these fields

00:45:15.826 --> 00:45:17.316 A:middle
to make sure that
they're the right values,

00:45:17.836 --> 00:45:19.066 A:middle
make sure that every key

00:45:19.066 --> 00:45:21.706 A:middle
that your app will ever
use exists in the schema.

00:45:22.646 --> 00:45:25.146 A:middle
And when you do that, you're
going to move it into production

00:45:25.146 --> 00:45:26.476 A:middle
and lock that schema in.

00:45:28.066 --> 00:45:31.406 A:middle
Additionally, all of these
indexes take up a decent amount

00:45:31.406 --> 00:45:33.306 A:middle
of space because
it has to make it

00:45:33.306 --> 00:45:35.926 A:middle
so that you can query
those records.

00:45:35.926 --> 00:45:38.216 A:middle
If you know you're never
going to query a value

00:45:38.216 --> 00:45:40.266 A:middle
like we know we're never
going to query for records

00:45:40.266 --> 00:45:43.636 A:middle
with just a blue background,
you can drop that index,

00:45:43.686 --> 00:45:47.036 A:middle
and this will help free up some
space in your app's database

00:45:47.036 --> 00:45:48.746 A:middle
or in your user's database.

00:45:51.716 --> 00:45:54.886 A:middle
So, finally, a couple
CloudKit tips and tricks.

00:45:56.286 --> 00:45:57.866 A:middle
So, we already went over this

00:45:57.866 --> 00:46:00.286 A:middle
in the intro talk
about error handling.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:57.866 --> 00:46:00.286 A:middle
in the intro talk
about error handling.

00:46:00.716 --> 00:46:02.346 A:middle
Please handle your
errors in CloudKit.

00:46:02.416 --> 00:46:03.486 A:middle
This is really important.

00:46:03.536 --> 00:46:07.496 A:middle
I know error handling is
hard and it's not fun to do,

00:46:07.946 --> 00:46:11.886 A:middle
but CloudKit is all based
on network communication.

00:46:12.526 --> 00:46:15.716 A:middle
And when you're talking over the
network, anything can go wrong.

00:46:16.526 --> 00:46:18.256 A:middle
You know, the network
can get dropped.

00:46:18.256 --> 00:46:20.096 A:middle
Because we have other
people talking

00:46:20.096 --> 00:46:21.706 A:middle
to the server, we
can get conflicts.

00:46:21.706 --> 00:46:22.526 A:middle
We can get errors.

00:46:23.146 --> 00:46:26.646 A:middle
All kinds of things can
happen, and as Paul said

00:46:26.646 --> 00:46:29.876 A:middle
in the first talk, this is the
difference between a working app

00:46:29.876 --> 00:46:30.976 A:middle
and a not working app.

00:46:30.976 --> 00:46:34.606 A:middle
It's not the difference between
a good app and a great app.

00:46:34.606 --> 00:46:36.096 A:middle
If you don't handle errors,

00:46:36.176 --> 00:46:39.446 A:middle
your app just isn't
going to work right.

00:46:39.646 --> 00:46:42.786 A:middle
In CloudKit also, we've tried
to avoid any sort of magic.

00:46:42.906 --> 00:46:46.376 A:middle
We don't want to try and handle
these errors for you and figure

00:46:46.376 --> 00:46:47.406 A:middle
out what might be best.

00:46:47.896 --> 00:46:50.556 A:middle
We want to just tell
you what happened.

00:46:50.556 --> 00:46:53.306 A:middle
We want you to be able to figure
out what you need to do next,

00:46:53.306 --> 00:46:56.896 A:middle
and we want to give you all
the information to do that.

00:46:57.136 --> 00:46:59.236 A:middle
So, keep in mind when you're
handling your errors here

00:46:59.236 --> 00:47:01.566 A:middle
that your operations
can have partial errors.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:46:59.236 --> 00:47:01.566 A:middle
that your operations
can have partial errors.

00:47:02.036 --> 00:47:05.316 A:middle
These partial errors when you're
using the NSOperation API,

00:47:05.316 --> 00:47:07.746 A:middle
you might be sending
up a batch of records.

00:47:08.406 --> 00:47:10.636 A:middle
And if you're saving them
to the public database,

00:47:10.736 --> 00:47:12.806 A:middle
it could be the case
that just one

00:47:12.806 --> 00:47:15.746 A:middle
of those records had a conflict
but the rest saved just fine.

00:47:16.526 --> 00:47:18.626 A:middle
If that happens, you're
going to get a partial error,

00:47:18.746 --> 00:47:20.876 A:middle
and inside of that, you're
going to find one error

00:47:20.876 --> 00:47:21.966 A:middle
for the record that failed.

00:47:22.816 --> 00:47:25.386 A:middle
If this was in a custom
zone, you might see

00:47:25.386 --> 00:47:27.276 A:middle
that as an atomic update error.

00:47:27.276 --> 00:47:30.006 A:middle
So, you might see that one
of those records failed,

00:47:30.006 --> 00:47:33.366 A:middle
and the rest got the
batch error in there.

00:47:34.356 --> 00:47:37.096 A:middle
And finally, we want
you to make sure

00:47:37.096 --> 00:47:39.436 A:middle
that you retry any
server busy errors.

00:47:40.176 --> 00:47:42.476 A:middle
It could be the case
that the, you know,

00:47:42.546 --> 00:47:45.046 A:middle
a bunch of people are going at
the servers at the same time

00:47:45.046 --> 00:47:46.236 A:middle
and the servers can't handle it

00:47:46.236 --> 00:47:47.906 A:middle
and they need clients
to back off.

00:47:48.096 --> 00:47:50.686 A:middle
It could also be that
your client is misbehaving

00:47:50.686 --> 00:47:52.286 A:middle
and hitting the server
too frequently,

00:47:52.286 --> 00:47:55.686 A:middle
and the server is saying,
"Slow down, buddy."

00:47:55.686 --> 00:47:57.556 A:middle
This is our way of
saying, "You know,

00:47:57.556 --> 00:47:58.656 A:middle
we need a little more time.

00:47:58.656 --> 00:48:00.796 A:middle
This request was OK, but
please try it again".


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:47:58.656 --> 00:48:00.796 A:middle
This request was OK, but
please try it again".

00:48:01.426 --> 00:48:03.556 A:middle
And anytime we give you
a server busy error,

00:48:03.556 --> 00:48:06.496 A:middle
we're going to hand back
a CKErrorRetryAfterKey.

00:48:07.026 --> 00:48:09.456 A:middle
This is a number of seconds
that we'd like you to wait

00:48:09.456 --> 00:48:11.426 A:middle
and retry your request.

00:48:14.116 --> 00:48:17.046 A:middle
So, limits, in the
keynote, it was mentioned

00:48:17.046 --> 00:48:18.936 A:middle
that CloudKit is
free with limits.

00:48:19.556 --> 00:48:21.326 A:middle
How do those limits work?

00:48:21.326 --> 00:48:25.116 A:middle
Well, anything stored in the
public database is counted

00:48:25.116 --> 00:48:26.336 A:middle
against your app's quota.

00:48:26.386 --> 00:48:29.766 A:middle
We give every app a
quota, and that's just

00:48:29.766 --> 00:48:30.626 A:middle
for the public database.

00:48:31.726 --> 00:48:34.086 A:middle
Anything you put in the
private database is counted

00:48:34.086 --> 00:48:35.516 A:middle
against the user's account.

00:48:35.706 --> 00:48:39.656 A:middle
So, every iCloud account gets
5 gigabytes of free storage,

00:48:40.146 --> 00:48:43.446 A:middle
but users might have bought
more, or they might have filled

00:48:43.446 --> 00:48:46.356 A:middle
up all that space with
emails or backups or photos.

00:48:46.866 --> 00:48:48.796 A:middle
So, every user is going
to have a different amount

00:48:48.796 --> 00:48:49.516 A:middle
of storage in there.

00:48:50.126 --> 00:48:52.216 A:middle
And because this is
kind of the user space

00:48:52.216 --> 00:48:54.116 A:middle
and it's shared space,
we want you to, you know,

00:48:54.346 --> 00:48:55.916 A:middle
remember to be nice
to your users.

00:48:55.916 --> 00:49:01.086 A:middle
It's technically free space for
you because it's theirs but,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:55.916 --> 00:49:01.086 A:middle
It's technically free space for
you because it's theirs but,

00:49:01.086 --> 00:49:03.326 A:middle
you know, don't fill it
up with unnecessary stuff.

00:49:03.906 --> 00:49:08.226 A:middle
So again, with the
limits, how much do you get

00:49:08.226 --> 00:49:09.096 A:middle
for your app container?

00:49:09.096 --> 00:49:10.766 A:middle
Well, what we're concerned

00:49:10.766 --> 00:49:13.666 A:middle
with here is customers
having a great experience,

00:49:14.166 --> 00:49:17.536 A:middle
and these limits that we've
specified here are really

00:49:17.576 --> 00:49:19.056 A:middle
to try and prevent abuse.

00:49:19.056 --> 00:49:20.936 A:middle
We don't want to
prevent legitimate use.

00:49:20.936 --> 00:49:23.446 A:middle
We just don't want
anyone abusing CloudKit.

00:49:24.496 --> 00:49:26.736 A:middle
And the numbers that we
give you here also scale

00:49:26.736 --> 00:49:28.356 A:middle
with the number of
users you have.

00:49:28.356 --> 00:49:29.946 A:middle
If you go on
developer.apple.com,

00:49:29.946 --> 00:49:32.666 A:middle
you can get the full breakdown
of the different values,

00:49:32.666 --> 00:49:36.916 A:middle
but as an example, if you had
10 million users of your app,

00:49:36.916 --> 00:49:39.486 A:middle
we're going to give you a
petabyte of asset storage,

00:49:39.486 --> 00:49:41.186 A:middle
10 terabytes of database
storage,

00:49:41.186 --> 00:49:44.676 A:middle
some pretty high transfer
limits, and this is all

00:49:44.766 --> 00:49:46.986 A:middle
for your public database
in your application.

00:49:49.556 --> 00:49:51.666 A:middle
So, finally, a note
on efficiency.

00:49:52.336 --> 00:49:54.916 A:middle
One thing about CloudKit
is, again,

00:49:54.916 --> 00:49:56.876 A:middle
it's a transport mechanism.

00:49:56.876 --> 00:49:59.976 A:middle
We are only there to talk to
the iCloud servers for you.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:00.676 --> 00:50:02.636 A:middle
We're not storing any records.

00:50:02.636 --> 00:50:03.796 A:middle
We're not caching records.

00:50:04.316 --> 00:50:06.456 A:middle
Anytime we give you back
a record, it's something

00:50:06.456 --> 00:50:07.536 A:middle
that we got from the server.

00:50:08.156 --> 00:50:10.206 A:middle
We're trying to be as
transparent about that

00:50:10.206 --> 00:50:13.876 A:middle
as possible and not do any
caching shenanigans here.

00:50:13.876 --> 00:50:16.326 A:middle
We're always just giving
you what the server gave us.

00:50:17.666 --> 00:50:21.116 A:middle
In terms of efficiency
though, you might remember

00:50:21.166 --> 00:50:23.226 A:middle
from the save policies
that we're only going

00:50:23.226 --> 00:50:25.366 A:middle
to save the values that
have changed on the records.

00:50:25.366 --> 00:50:27.856 A:middle
So, we try and be smart about
what we send over the wire.

00:50:29.106 --> 00:50:30.846 A:middle
When we're sending up assets,

00:50:30.956 --> 00:50:33.586 A:middle
those can be potentially
really big blobs of data,

00:50:34.246 --> 00:50:36.496 A:middle
and that data is
transferred efficiently.

00:50:36.496 --> 00:50:38.896 A:middle
So, if the server already
has a copy of a file,

00:50:39.306 --> 00:50:40.306 A:middle
we won't re-upload it.

00:50:40.486 --> 00:50:42.236 A:middle
If we already have
that file locally,

00:50:42.236 --> 00:50:46.506 A:middle
we don't need to re-download it.

00:50:46.696 --> 00:50:50.076 A:middle
So, in summary, we're really
excited about CloudKit here.

00:50:50.076 --> 00:50:52.446 A:middle
We've built a lot of
really great features

00:50:52.926 --> 00:50:55.306 A:middle
and it's something that
we actually use at Apple.

00:50:55.306 --> 00:50:58.466 A:middle
We've built iCloud Drive, we've
built iCloud Photos on top

00:50:58.466 --> 00:51:02.326 A:middle
of this, and we want you guys to
start using the same technology


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

